\section{Mathematical Formulation, Regularization, and Thermal Shift}
\label{sec:mathematical_formulation}

This section formalizes the reduced Geometric Singular Perturbation Theory (GSPT) description of the Stable Boundary Layer (SBL). The formulation separates the rapid subgrid-scale turbulent adjustment from the slower surface-energy and rotational evolution.

\subsection{Fast-Slow Structure and Dimensional Scaling}
\label{subsec:mathematical_fast_slow}

The concrete prognostic system for the state vector $\mathbf{x} = (U, V, T_s, e)^T$ is given by:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{dU}{dt} &= f(V - V_g) - C_D \frac{\sqrt{U^2+V^2}}{h} U \Phi_m(e), \\
\frac{dV}{dt} &= -f(U - U_g) - C_D \frac{\sqrt{U^2+V^2}}{h} V \Phi_m(e), \\
\frac{dT_s}{dt} &= \frac{1}{C_{\text{skin}}}\left(R_{\downarrow} - \sigma_{\text{SB}}T_s^4 - \lambda\frac{T_s - T_{\text{deep}}}{d_{\text{soil}}} - \rho c_p C_H\sqrt{U^2+V^2}\,(T_s - T_a)\Phi_h(e)\right), \\
\varepsilon\frac{de}{dt} &= l_0 \left[\eta\,\gamma\,(U^2+V^2) - K\,G(T_s)\right] \Phi_m(e) - (e+\delta).
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:mathematical_full_system}
\end{equation}

Here, $f$ is the Coriolis frequency, $h$ is the boundary layer depth, $C_{\text{skin}}$ is the surface thermal capacity, and $K$ is the kinematic buoyant acceleration scale. The background minimum TKE floor is represented by $\delta > 0$, ensuring the fast subsystem possesses a physical boundary limit at $e = -\delta$. The transport functions are modeled as $\Phi_{m,h}(e) = \sqrt{e + \delta}$ to maintain consistency with classical mixing-length theory.

In the multi-layer SCM closure, the constant scale height $h$ is replaced by an emergent effective scale height $h_{\text{eff}}$ that feeds resolved momentum back into the damping coefficients:
\begin{equation}
h_{\text{eff}} = \operatorname{clamp}\!\left((1-w)h_0 + w\,\frac{\sqrt{U^2 + V^2 + \delta_u}}{\max(|f|, f_{\text{floor}})},\; h_{\min},\; h_{\max}\right),
\label{eq:heff_emergent}
\end{equation}
where $w \in [0,1]$ is the non-local blend weight and $\delta_u$ is a small velocity floor regularizer.

\subsection{Geometric Analysis: Boundary Crossings vs. Fold Catastrophes}
\label{subsec:geometric_consequences}

GSPT allows us to formally distinguish between two distinct physical transitions that are often conflated in boundary-layer literature:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{The Boundary Crossing:} This occurs when the fast trajectory crosses the physical threshold $e = 0$. Here, the critical manifold remains normally hyperbolic, but the transport coefficients transition to their background molecular/residual values.
    \item \textbf{The Fold Catastrophe ($\mathcal{C}_{\text{fold}}$):} This is an emergent property of the coupled slow flow on $\mathcal{M}_0$. It occurs where the tangent space of the critical manifold becomes parallel to the fast direction, satisfying:
    \begin{equation}
    \mathcal{C}_{\text{fold}} = \left\{ (U, V, T_s, e) \in \mathcal{M}_0 \ \middle|\ \det \left( \text{D}_{\mathbf{y}} e^*_{\xi} \right) = 0 \right\}.
    \end{equation}
    In equivalent SEB form, this corresponds to a loss of slow thermodynamic Jacobian rank:
    \begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial}{\partial T_s}\left(R_{\downarrow} - \sigma_{\mathrm{SB}}T_s^4 - \rho c_p C_H\sqrt{e^*(T_s,U,V)+\delta}(T_s-T_a) - \frac{K_g}{d_g}(T_s-T_g)\right)=0.
    \label{eq:seb_fold_condition}
    \end{equation}
    At this fold line, normal hyperbolicity is completely lost, forcing the slow flow to jump along the fast fibers toward the stable laminar sheet—manifesting physically as SBL collapse.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Tri-Height Observability Diagnostics}
\label{subsec:triheight_observability}

To track how $h_{\text{eff}}$ modifies vertical structure during transition, we diagnose three operational heights in SCM outputs:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
h_D &= \inf\{z : D(z) < 0.05\}, \qquad D(z)=K_m(z)/\max_z K_m(z),\\
h_e &= \inf\{z : e(z) < \epsilon_e\},\\
h_{\partial e} &= \operatorname*{arg\,max}_z\left(-\frac{\partial e}{\partial z}\right).
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:triheight_diagnostics}
\end{equation}
These correspond to the geometric decoupling interface, energetic turbulent floor, and maximum-curvature transition height, respectively.